## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three compounding bugs** in this component — any one alone would cause problems, but together they create an exponential listener accumulation that grinds the browser to a halt.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Effect Runs on Every Render)

```jsx
// ❌ No dependency array — runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
});
```

Without the `[]` dependency array, React re-runs this effect after **every single render**. The cascade looks like this:

```
Mount → effect runs → adds 2 listeners
User scrolls → handler fires → setState × 3 → re-render
Re-render → effect runs AGAIN → adds 2 MORE listeners
User scrolls → now 2 handlers fire → setState × 6 → 2 re-renders
Each re-render → effect runs AGAIN → adds 2 MORE listeners
...
```

This is **exponential growth** triggered by the component's own normal operation.

---

## Bug #2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Never Removed)

```jsx
// ❌ No return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // Nothing returned — React has no way to clean up
});
```

React's `useEffect` cleanup mechanism works like this:

| Lifecycle Event | With Cleanup | Without Cleanup |
|---|---|---|
| Before next effect runs | Calls cleanup fn, removes old listeners | Nothing — old listeners stack |
| Component unmounts | Calls cleanup fn, removes listeners | Nothing — listeners become zombies |

When the component unmounts (user navigates away), every listener that was ever added continues to:
- **Hold a reference** to the component's closure and state setters (`setScrollY`, etc.)
- **Prevent garbage collection** of those closure objects
- **Actively fire** on scroll/resize events, calling state setters on an unmounted component

On the next navigation back to the page, a fresh batch is added on top of the orphaned ones. Each round-trip **permanently grows** the listener pool.

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions Break `removeEventListener`

```jsx
// ❌ New function instance created on every call — unremovable
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { ... }); // ← different object reference, does NOTHING
```

`removeEventListener` uses **reference equality** to find the handler to remove. An arrow function expression creates a brand-new object in memory every time it's evaluated. Even if you added a cleanup return here, it would silently fail:

```jsx
// This appears to work but does NOTHING — the two () => {} are different objects
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => setScrollY(window.scrollY));
    return () => window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => setScrollY(window.scrollY)); // ❌ no-op
});
```

You must hold a **stable reference** to pass the same function to both `addEventListener` and `removeEventListener`.

---

## Bonus Bug #4 — Stale Closure on `lastScrollY`

```jsx
const [lastScrollY, setLastScrollY] = useState(0);

useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
        // ❌ `lastScrollY` is captured from the render scope at the time this
        // closure was created. It's frozen at whatever value existed then.
        setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollY ? 'down' : 'up');
    });
});
```

Because `lastScrollY` is a state variable, its value is captured in the closure when the listener is created. The handler can never see updates to `lastScrollY` made after it was registered. The only reason this "kind of works" in the buggy version is that the missing dependency array causes the effect (and thus the listener) to be recreated on every render — accidentally refreshing the captured value, but at the cost of the avalanche of extra listeners.

The fix is `useRef`, which always exposes the current value via `.current` and never goes stale inside a closure.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Instantly Obvious

In development, React 18 Strict Mode **intentionally double-invokes effects** to surface missing cleanups:

```
Mount → effect runs → 2 listeners added
Simulated unmount → no cleanup → listeners orphaned
Re-mount → effect runs → 2 more listeners added
```

Your app starts with 4 listeners instead of 2 in dev mode. When you scroll, the doubled re-renders add 4 more each time. What would be a gradual production leak becomes an immediately perceptible freeze in development — which is exactly the feature working as intended.

---

## Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // ✅ useRef instead of useState for lastScrollY:
    //    - Mutations don't trigger re-renders (no render cascade)
    //    - Always exposes the live value via .current (no stale closure)
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // ✅ Named functions — stable references that removeEventListener can match
        function handleScroll() {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // ✅ Read from ref — always the current value, never stale
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');

            // ✅ Mutate ref directly — no re-render triggered
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY;

            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        }

        function handleResize() {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        }

        // Register listeners
        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // ✅ Cleanup function — React calls this:
        //    1. Before re-running the effect (if deps change)
        //    2. When the component unmounts
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll); // ✅ Same reference — works
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize); // ✅ Same reference — works
        };

    }, []); // ✅ Empty array — effect runs once on mount, cleans up on unmount

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Fixes

| Problem | Root Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Listeners added every render | Missing `[]` dependency array | Add `[]` — effect runs once |
| Listeners never removed on unmount | No cleanup return | Return cleanup fn calling `removeEventListener` |
| Cleanup would silently no-op | Anonymous arrow functions | Named functions with stable references |
| Stale `lastScrollY` in closure | State var captured at closure creation | `useRef` — always reads live `.current` |

The corrected component registers exactly **2 listeners on mount** and removes **exactly those 2 on unmount**, regardless of how many times the user navigates away and back.

